# Spec-driven development (Road Safety Game)

| Doc | Role |
|-----|------|
| `docs/core-game-rules.md` | **Canonical gameplay rules** — TMX zones, levels, scoring, scenarios |
| `docs/specs/2026-06-26-level-system-design.md` | **Level system architecture** — curriculum, unlock graph, new-level checklist |
| `docs/specs/*.md` | **One change** — requirements and acceptance criteria |
| `AGENTS.md` (workspace root `CarGame/`) | Preferences + stable facts |

Do not implement level or zone behaviour that contradicts `docs/core-game-rules.md` unless the user's spec explicitly changes a rule and includes rollout notes.

Features touching level catalog, unlocks, or curriculum must cite **§7** in core rules and the level-system design spec.

Per-feature specs live in `docs/specs/`; **one spec = one change**.

## When the user references a spec

If the task mentions `docs/specs/<file>.md`, `@docs/specs/`, or *"implement per spec"*:

1. **Read the spec first** — goal, non-goals, requirements, acceptance criteria. Cross-check cited sections in `docs/core-game-rules.md`.
2. **Implement against it** — do not edit the spec file unless the user explicitly changes requirements.
3. **Before finishing** — verify every acceptance-criteria checkbox you can; note manual-only items for the user.
4. **Update the spec kit** — same task/PR as code (see **Keep the spec kit in sync** below).
5. **Session boundaries** — if the feature touches driving lessons, radio, or assistant visibility, respect lifecycle rules in workspace `AGENTS.md`.

## When to create a spec (suggest if missing)

| Write a spec first | Chat + `AGENTS.md` is enough |
|--------------------|------------------------------|
| New/changed zone types or level pass/fail rules | Typo / copy fix |
| New TMX conventions across multiple maps | One-line bug in a single file |
| Scoring / rubric / report behaviour | Dependency bump |
| New level, scenario, or unlock rule | Styling-only HUD tweak |

If the user starts a non-trivial feature without a spec, **offer** to copy `docs/specs/_template.md` → `docs/specs/YYYY-MM-DD-short-name.md` and fill goal + acceptance criteria before coding. Do not block tiny fixes.

## Specs vs plans

| Artifact | Use for |
|----------|---------|
| `docs/specs/*.md` | **What** to build — requirements, acceptance criteria (source of truth for one feature) |
| `.cursor/plans/*.plan.md` | **How** to sequence a large effort — todos, exploration; link from the spec if both exist |

Prefer a dated spec for shippable features; use plans only for multi-session architecture or when the user attaches a plan file.

## New spec workflow

1. Copy `docs/specs/_template.md` → `docs/specs/YYYY-MM-DD-short-feature-name.md`.
2. Fill goal, scope, acceptance criteria, affected surfaces (TMX, `driving_game.dart`, level catalog, UI). List affected `core-game-rules.md` sections in Background.
3. User prompt: *Implement per `docs/specs/<filename>.md`. Do not edit the spec file.*

See `docs/specs/README.md` for the full checklist.

## Keep the spec kit in sync (required)

When you **build or change** gameplay, zones, levels, scoring, scenarios, or player-facing rules — **update documentation in the same task**.

**This is automatic.** Do not wait for the user to ask. Apply the **completion gate** below before marking any non-trivial task done.

### Agent completion gate (run before every task ends)

If the task is **not** in [Skip doc updates](#skip-doc-updates-only-when), complete every row that applies:

| Step | Action | When |
|------|--------|------|
| 1 | Edit matching **§** in [`docs/core-game-rules.md`](../../docs/core-game-rules.md) | Gameplay, zones, scoring, scenarios |
| 2 | Update [`docs/specs/2026-06-26-level-system-design.md`](../../docs/specs/2026-06-26-level-system-design.md) | Curriculum, unlock graph, new-level definition of done |
| 3 | Dated spec — check acceptance criteria, **Status**, **Implementation log** line | Feature tracked in or implementing `docs/specs/YYYY-MM-DD-….md` |
| 4 | Create retroactive `docs/specs/YYYY-MM-DD-….md` | Shipped non-trivial behaviour with no existing spec |
| 5 | **Completion summary** — list spec-kit files updated, or state *no doc change — internal refactor only* | Always |

**Do not update `AGENTS.md`** for routine spec-kit sync — only for new **stable** preferences or ops facts agents must always know.

### What to update (detail)

| You changed… | Update |
|--------------|--------|
| **Gameplay / zone / level / scoring logic** | [`docs/core-game-rules.md`](../../docs/core-game-rules.md) — edit the matching § section(s); add rows/rules if new behaviour |
| **Level catalog, unlocks, curriculum order** | [`docs/specs/2026-06-26-level-system-design.md`](../../docs/specs/2026-06-26-level-system-design.md) + core rules §7 |
| **Feature you implemented from a spec** | That `docs/specs/YYYY-MM-DD-….md` — check off acceptance criteria; set **Status** Done; fill **Implementation log** |
| **Non-trivial feature without an existing spec** | Create `docs/specs/YYYY-MM-DD-….md` **after** shipping (or before if greenfield) so the change is recorded |
| **Stable preference or recurring ops fact** | workspace [`AGENTS.md`](../../../AGENTS.md) — one bullet only; do not duplicate `core-game-rules.md` |

### When implementing (even without a spec)

1. **Before coding** — skim `docs/core-game-rules.md` for sections you might affect; cite them if you create a spec.
2. **After coding** — run the [Agent completion gate](#agent-completion-gate-run-before-every-task-ends); if behaviour differs from `core-game-rules.md`, **update that file** (intentional change) or fix the code (bug).
3. **Tell the user** — in the completion summary, list which spec-kit files were updated (or explicitly "no doc change — internal refactor only").

### Skip doc updates only when

- Pure refactor with **zero** player-visible or gameplay behaviour change
- Typo, styling, or dependency bump with no rule change
- Test-only or comment-only changes

If unsure whether gameplay changed, **update `core-game-rules.md`** — stale rules mislead future agents more than an extra bullet.
